---
import MainLayout from "../../layouts/MainLayout.astro";
import GearIntro from "../../components/GearIntro.astro";
import { getEntry, render } from "astro:content";
import VideoCard from "../../components/VideoCard.astro";

const gear = await getEntry("gear", "push");
if (!gear) throw new Error("Gear not found");
const { Content } = await render(gear);

const videos = [
  {
    id: "fTUcEYF4aPA",
    title: "Getting Started",
    description: "Create an account, register Push, get Live, connect Push.",
  },
  {
    id: "HM8EmM5C3Ls",
    title: "Creating Beats",
    description: "Create drumloops with the step sequencer and drumpads.",
  },
  {
    id: "kIovU2tpNWg",
    title: "Playing Chords and Melodies",
    description: "Discover Note mode and scales.",
  },
  {
    id: "amvzZdlU3Fg",
    title: "Tweaking and Mixing",
    description: "Automate parameters and refine your mix.",
  },
  {
    id: "9CHyB70Hz30",
    title: "Session Mode",
    description: "Improvise with your musical ideas using clips and scenes.",
  },
  {
    id: "0rxsPCF0j-4",
    title: "Pad Sensitivity",
    description: "Adjust the sensitivity and velocity curve of the pads.",
  },
  {
    id: "XQQNHgY4NnM",
    title: "Workflow",
    description: "From ideas to song parts.",
  },
  {
    id: "zsNskXJHoBw",
    title: "Step Sequencing",
    description: "Create chords and melodies with the melodic step sequencer.",
  },
  {
    id: "sSRe27_fDak",
    title: "Step Automation",
    description:
      "Change parameter values of Live instruments and effects per step.",
  },
  {
    id: "s5aZwT53Djo",
    title: "Slicing Audio Samples",
    description:
      "Slice audio samples to pads and play them melodically or as a drum kit.",
  },
  {
    id: "1xxWdvotAlo",
    title: "How to Make Beats",
    description:
      "Build beats from scratch using Push 1 with the step sequencer and drumpads.",
  },
];
---

<MainLayout title={gear.data.title} description={gear.data.description}>
  <GearIntro
    title={gear.data.title}
    description={gear.data.description}
    url={gear.data.url}
    ctaLabel="Official Manual"
  />

  <div class="section-card video-section">
    <div class="video-section__header">
      <h2>Learn Push 1</h2>
      <p>
        11 official tutorials from Ableton covering everything from first setup
        to making beats. Videos sourced from <a
          href="https://www.ableton.com/en/help/learn-push-1/"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer">ableton.com/en/help/learn-push-1</a
        >.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="video-grid">
      {
        videos.map((v) => (
          <VideoCard id={v.id} title={v.title} description={v.description} />
        ))
      }
    </div>
  </div>

  <article class="prose mt-8">
    <Content />
  </article>

  <div class="section-card using-push-section">
    <h2>Using Push 1</h2>
    <p>
      Ableton Push 1 is an instrument for song creation that provides hands-on
      control of melody and harmony, beats, sounds, and song structure. In the
      studio, Push 1 allows you to quickly create clips that populate Live's
      Session View as you work entirely from the hardware. On stage, Push 1
      serves as a powerful instrument for clip launching.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushOverview.png"
        alt="Overview of Push 1's Controls"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Overview of Push 1's Controls</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Much of Push 1's behavior depends on which mode it is in, as well as on
      which type of track is selected.
    </p>

    <h3 id="setup">Setup</h3>
    <p>
      Setting up the Push 1 hardware is mostly automatic. As long as Live is
      running, Push 1 will be automatically detected as soon as it is connected
      to a USB port on your computer. After connection, Push 1 can be used
      immediately. It is not necessary to install drivers and Push 1 does not
      need to be manually configured in Live's Settings.
    </p>

    <h3 id="browsing-and-loading-sounds">Browsing and Loading Sounds</h3>
    <p>
      You can browse and load sounds directly from Push 1, without needing to
      use Live's browser. This is done in Push 1's Browse Mode.
    </p>
    <p>Press Push 1's <kbd>Browse</kbd> button.</p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushBrowseButton.png"
        alt="The Browse Button"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>The Browse Button</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      In Browse Mode, the display shows all of your available sounds and
      effects, as well as locations from the Places section of Live's browser.
      The display is divided into columns. The far left column shows either the
      specific type of device being browsed or the Places label. Each column to
      the right shows the next subfolder (if any exist). Use the <kbd>In</kbd> and
      <kbd>Out</kbd> buttons to shift the display to the right or left, allowing you
      to browse deeper levels of subfolders or view a larger number of presets on
      the display.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushInOutButtons.png"
        alt="In and Out Buttons"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>In and Out Buttons</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Navigate up via the Selection Control button (the first row below the
      display) in each column. Navigate down one folder via the State Control
      button for each level (the second row below the display). Samples and
      presets from official Packs or Live's Core Library will preview when
      selected in the browser. To load a device preset, press the green button
      on the right. To load the default preset of the selected device, press the
      green button on the left.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushBrowseLoadButtons.png"
        alt="Loading Devices or Device Presets in Browse Mode"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Loading Devices or Device Presets in Browse Mode</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      You can scroll quickly through folders and subfolders via the encoders.
      Holding <kbd>Shift</kbd> while pressing the up or down buttons will move by
      a whole page.
    </p>
    <p>
      After pressing a device or preset load button, the button will turn amber.
      This indicates that the currently selected entry is loaded; if you
      navigate to a different entry, the button will turn green again. Pressing
      an amber load button will load the next entry in the list, allowing you to
      quickly try out presets or devices.
    </p>
    <p>
      What you see when in Browse Mode depends on the device that was last
      selected. If you were working with an instrument, Browse Mode will show
      you replacement instruments. If you were working with an effect, you will
      see effects. When starting with an empty MIDI track, the display shows all
      of your available sounds, instruments, drum kits, effects, and Max for
      Live devices, as well as VST and Audio Units plug-ins.
    </p>

    <h3 id="playing-and-programming-beats">Playing and Programming Beats</h3>
    <p>To create beats using Push 1, first make sure Note Mode is enabled.</p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushNoteModeButton.png"
        alt="The Note Mode Button"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>The Note Mode Button</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Then use Browse Mode to load one of the Drum Rack presets from Live's
      library.
    </p>
    <p>
      When working with a MIDI track containing a Drum Rack, Push 1's 8x8 pad
      grid can be configured in a few different ways, depending on the state of
      the <kbd>Note</kbd> button. Pressing this button cycles between three different
      modes.
    </p>

    <h4 id="loop-selector">Loop Selector</h4>
    <p>
      When the Loop Selector layout is enabled, the pads are divided into three
      sections, allowing you to simultaneously play, step sequence and adjust
      the length of your clip.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushDrumLayout.png"
        alt="The Pad Grid When Working With Drums"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>The Pad Grid When Working With Drums</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      The 16 Drum Rack pads are laid out, like Live's Drum Rack, in the classic
      4x4 arrangement, allowing for real-time playing. The Drum Rack pad colors
      indicate the following:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Bright yellow</strong> — this pad contains a sound.</li>
      <li><strong>Dull yellow</strong> — this pad is empty.</li>
      <li><strong>Green</strong> — this pad is currently-playing.</li>
      <li><strong>Light Blue</strong> — this pad is selected.</li>
      <li><strong>Dark blue</strong> — this pad is soloed.</li>
      <li><strong>Orange</strong> — this pad is muted.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      When working with Drum Racks that contain a larger number of pads, use
      Push 1's touch strip or the <kbd>Octave Up</kbd> and <kbd>Octave Down</kbd
      > keys to move up/down by 16 pads. Hold <kbd>Shift</kbd> while using the touch
      strip or Octave keys to move by single rows.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushOctaveUpDown.png"
        alt="Octave Up/Down Buttons"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Octave Up/Down Buttons</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Holding the <kbd>Note</kbd> button gives you momentary access to the 16 Velocities
      layout. You can also lock the alternate layout in place by holding <kbd
        >Shift</kbd
      > and pressing the <kbd>Note</kbd> button. To unlock the 16 Velocities layout,
      press the <kbd>Note</kbd> button again.
    </p>

    <h4 id="16-velocities-mode">16 Velocities Mode</h4>
    <p>
      Press the <kbd>Layout</kbd> button to switch to the 16 Velocities layout. In
      this mode, the bottom right 16 pads represent 16 different velocities for the
      selected Drum Rack pad. Tap one of the velocity pads to enter steps at that
      velocity.
    </p>
    <p>
      Holding the <kbd>Note</kbd> button gives you momentary access to the loop length
      controls. You can also lock the loop length controls in place by holding <kbd
        >Shift</kbd
      > and pressing the <kbd>Note</kbd> button. To unlock the loop length pads, press
      the <kbd>Note</kbd> button again.
    </p>

    <h4 id="64-pad-mode">64-Pad Mode</h4>
    <p>
      In addition to the Loop Selector and 16 Velocities layouts, you can also
      use the entire 8x8 pad grid for real-time drum playing. This is useful
      when working with very large drum kits, such as those created by slicing.
      To toggle to 64-pad mode, press the <kbd>Note Mode</kbd> button a second time.
      Pressing <kbd>Note</kbd> again will then toggle back to the Loop Selector layout,
      allowing you to quickly get back to step sequencing. The pad colors in 64-pad
      mode are the same as those used in the three-section layout.
    </p>
    <p>
      When moving back and forth between the three layouts, the 16 pads
      available for step sequencing will not change automatically. You may still
      need to use the touch strip or Octave keys in order to see the specific 16
      pads you want.
    </p>
    <p>
      Holding the <kbd>Note</kbd> button gives you momentary access to the loop length
      controls. You can also lock the loop length controls in place by holding <kbd
        >Shift</kbd
      > and pressing the <kbd>Note</kbd> button. To unlock the loop length pads, press
      the <kbd>Note</kbd> button again.
    </p>

    <h4 id="loading-individual-drums">Loading Individual Drums</h4>
    <p>
      Browse Mode can also be used to load or replace individual pads within a
      loaded Drum Rack. To switch between browsing Drum Racks and single pads,
      press the <kbd>Device</kbd> button to show the devices on the track.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushDeviceButton.png"
        alt="Device Button"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Device Button</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      By default, the Drum Rack is selected, as indicated by the arrow in the
      display. To select an individual pad instead, tap that pad, then press the
      selection button below the pad's name.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushDrumPadSelection.png"
        alt="Selecting an Individual Pad in a Drum Rack"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Selecting an Individual Pad in a Drum Rack</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Now, entering Browse Mode again will allow you to load or replace the
      sound of only the selected pad. Once in Browse Mode, tapping other pads
      will select them for browsing, allowing you to quickly load or replace
      multiple sounds within the loaded Drum Rack.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Additional Pad Options:</strong> To copy a pad to a different location
      in your Drum Rack, hold the <kbd>Duplicate</kbd> button and press the pad you'd
      like to copy. While continuing to hold <kbd>Duplicate</kbd>, press the pad
      where you'd like to paste the copied pad. Note that this will replace the
      destination pad's devices (and thus its sound) but will not replace any
      existing notes already recorded for that pad.
    </p>

    <h4 id="step-sequencing-beats">Step Sequencing Beats</h4>
    <p>
      Tapping a pad also enables it for step sequencing. To select a pad without
      playing it, press and hold the <kbd>Select</kbd> button while tapping a pad.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushSelectButton.png"
        alt="Select Button"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Select Button</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      To record notes with the step sequencer, tap the pads in the step
      sequencer controls to place notes in the clip where you want them. The
      clip will begin playing as soon as you tap a step. By default, each step
      sequencer pad corresponds to a 16th note, but you can change the step size
      via the buttons in the <kbd>Scene/Grid</kbd> section.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushSceneGridButtons.png"
        alt="Scene/Grid Buttons"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Scene/Grid Buttons</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      As the clip plays, the currently playing step is indicated by the moving
      green pad in the step sequencer section. When Record is enabled, the
      moving pad will be red. Tapping a step that already has a note will delete
      that note. Press and hold the <kbd>Mute</kbd> button while tapping a step to
      deactivate it without deleting it. Press and hold <kbd>Solo</kbd> button while
      tapping a pad to solo that sound.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushMuteSoloButtons.png"
        alt="Mute and Solo Buttons"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Mute and Solo Buttons</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>The pad colors in the step sequencer section indicate the following:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Unlit</strong> — this step doesn't contain a note.</li>
      <li>
        <strong>Blue</strong> — this step contains a note. Darker blues indicate higher
        velocities.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Dull yellow</strong> — this step contains a note, but the note is
        muted.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Light Red</strong> — the right two columns of pads will turn red if
        triplets are selected as the step size. In this case, these pads are not active;
        only the first six pads in each row of steps can be used.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushTripletSteps.png"
        alt="When Triplets are Selected, the Red Steps are Unavailable"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>
        When Triplets are Selected, the Red Steps are Unavailable
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      To delete all notes for a pad, press and hold <kbd>Delete</kbd> while tapping
      the pad. Note that this will only delete notes that are within the current loop.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushDeleteButton.png"
        alt="Delete Button"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Delete Button</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h4 id="real-time-recording">Real-time Recording</h4>
    <p>
      Drum patterns can also be recorded in real-time by playing the Drum Rack
      pads. Follow these steps to record in real-time:
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        If you want to record with a click track, press the <kbd>Metronome</kbd> button
        to enable Live's built-in click.
        <figure>
          <img
            src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushMetronomeButton.png"
            alt="Metronome Button"
            loading="lazy"
          />
          <figcaption>Metronome Button</figcaption>
        </figure>
      </li>
      <li>
        Press the <kbd>Record</kbd> button to begin recording.
        <figure>
          <img
            src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushRecordButton.png"
            alt="Record Button"
            loading="lazy"
          />
          <figcaption>Record Button</figcaption>
        </figure>
      </li>
      <li>
        Now any Drum Rack pads you play will be recorded to the clip. Pressing <kbd
          >Record</kbd
        > again will stop recording but will continue playing back the clip. Pressing
        <kbd>Record</kbd> a third time will enable overdub mode, allowing you to record
        into the clip while it plays back. Subsequent presses continue to toggle between
        playback and overdub.
      </li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      Pressing <kbd>New</kbd> stops playback of the currently selected clip and prepares
      Live to record a new clip on the currently selected track. This allows you to
      practice before recording a new idea. By default, pressing <kbd>New</kbd> also
      duplicates all clips that are playing on other tracks to a new scene and continues
      playing them back seamlessly. This behavior can be changed by changing the Workflow
      mode in Push 1's User Preferences.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushNewButtton.png"
        alt="New Button"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>New Button</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h4 id="fixed-length-recording">Fixed Length Recording</h4>
    <p>
      Press the <kbd>Fixed Length</kbd> button to set the size of new clips to a predetermined
      length.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushFixedLengthButton.png"
        alt="Fixed Length Button"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Fixed Length Button</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>Press and hold <kbd>Fixed Length</kbd> to set the recording length.</p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushSettingFixedLength.png"
        alt="Fixed Length Recording Options"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Fixed Length Recording Options</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      When <kbd>Fixed Length</kbd> is disabled, new clips will continue to record
      until you press the <kbd>Record</kbd>, <kbd>New</kbd> or <kbd
        >Play/Stop</kbd
      > buttons. Enabling <kbd>Fixed Length</kbd> while recording will switch recording
      off and loop the last few bars of the clip, depending on the Fixed Length setting.
    </p>

    <h3 id="additional-recording-options">Additional Recording Options</h3>

    <h4 id="recording-with-repeat">Recording with Repeat</h4>
    <p>
      With Push 1's <kbd>Repeat</kbd> button enabled, you can hold down a pad to play
      or record a stream of continuous, rhythmically-even notes. This is useful for
      recording steady hi-hat patterns, for example. Varying your finger pressure
      on the pad will change the volume of the repeated notes.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushRepeatButton.png"
        alt="Repeat Button"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Repeat Button</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      The repeat rate is set with the <kbd>Scene/Grid</kbd> buttons. Note that Push
      1 "remembers" the <kbd>Repeat</kbd> button's state and setting for each track.
    </p>
    <p>
      If you press and release <kbd>Repeat</kbd> quickly, the button will stay on.
      If you press and hold, the button will turn off when released, allowing for
      momentary control of repeated notes.
    </p>
    <p>
      Turn up the Swing knob to apply swing to the repeated notes. When you
      touch the knob, the display will show the amount of swing.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushSwingKnob.jpg"
        alt="Swing Knob"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Swing Knob</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h4 id="quantizing">Quantizing</h4>
    <p>
      Pressing Push 1's <kbd>Quantize</kbd> button will snap notes to the grid in
      the selected clip.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushQuantizeButton.png"
        alt="Quantize Button"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Quantize Button</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Press and hold <kbd>Quantize</kbd> to change the quantization options:
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushQuantizeOptions.png"
        alt="Quantization Options"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Quantization Options</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Swing Amount</strong> determines the amount of swing that will be
        applied to the quantized notes.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Quantize To</strong> sets the nearest note value to which notes will
        be quantized.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Quantize Amount</strong> determines the amount that notes can be moved
        from their original positions.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Record Quantize</strong> automatically quantizes notes while recording.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      When working with drums, press and hold <kbd>Quantize</kbd> and press a Drum
      Rack pad to quantize only that drum's notes in the current clip.
    </p>

    <h3 id="playing-melodies-and-harmonies">Playing Melodies and Harmonies</h3>
    <p>
      After working on a beat, you'll want to create a new track so that you can
      work on a bassline, harmony parts, etc. Press the <kbd>Add Track</kbd> button
      to add a new MIDI track to your Live Set.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushAddTrackButton.png"
        alt="Add Track Button"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Add Track Button</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Press and hold the <kbd>Add Track</kbd> button to select between Audio, MIDI
      and Return tracks.
    </p>
    <p>
      Adding a track puts Push 1 into Browse mode, so you can immediately load
      an instrument. After loading your instrument, make sure <kbd
        >Note Mode</kbd
      > is enabled.
    </p>
    <p>
      When working with a MIDI track containing an instrument, Push 1's 8x8 pad
      grid automatically configures itself to play notes. By default, every note
      on the grid is in the key of C major. The bottom left pad plays C1. Moving
      upward, each pad is a fourth higher. Moving to the right, each pad is the
      next note in the C major scale.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushCMajorScale.png"
        alt="C Major Scale"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>C Major Scale</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>The pad colors help you to stay oriented as you play:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Blue</strong> — this note is the root note of the key (e.g., C).
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>White</strong> — this note is in the scale, but is not the root.
      </li>
      <li><strong>Green</strong> — the currently-playing note.</li>
      <li><strong>Red</strong> — the currently-playing note when recording.</li>
    </ul>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushCMajorTriad.png"
        alt="C Major Chord"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>C Major Chord</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Holding the <kbd>Note</kbd> button gives you momentary access to the loop length
      controls, which appear in the top row of pads. You can lock the loop length
      controls in place by holding <kbd>Shift</kbd> and pressing the <kbd
        >Note</kbd
      > button.
    </p>

    <h4 id="playing-in-other-keys">Playing in Other Keys</h4>
    <p>
      Press Push 1's <kbd>Scales</kbd> button to change the selected key and/or scale.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushScalesButton.png"
        alt="Scales Button"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Scales Button</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Using the display and the Selection and State Control buttons, you can
      change the key played by the pad grid.
    </p>
    <p>
      By default, the pads and scale selection options indicate major scales.
      You can change to a variety of other scale types using the first encoder,
      or the two buttons below the display on the far left.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushScalesSelection.png"
        alt="Key and Scale Selection"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Key and Scale Selection</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      In addition to changing the key, you can also change the layout of the
      grid:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Fixed Y/N:</strong> When Fixed Mode is on, the notes on the pad grid
        remain in the same positions when you change keys; the bottom-left pad will
        always play C, except in keys that don't contain a C, in which case the bottom-left
        pad will play the nearest note in the key. When Fixed is off, the notes on
        the pad grid shift so that the bottom-left pad always plays the root of the
        selected key.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>In Key/Chromatic:</strong> With In Key selected, the pad grid is effectively
        "folded" so that only notes within the key are available. In Chromatic Mode,
        the pad grid contains all notes. Notes that are in the key are lit, while
        notes that are not in the key are unlit.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Holding the <kbd>Shift</kbd> button while in Scales mode allows you to access
      additional note layout options.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushNoteLayouts.png"
        alt="Additional Note Layout Options"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Additional Note Layout Options</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      The "4th" and "3rd" options refer to the note interval that the grid is
      based on, while the ^ and &gt; symbols refer to the rotation of the grid.
      The "Sequent" options lay out all notes in order and are useful if you
      need a very large range of notes.
    </p>
    <p>
      The last settings chosen in the Scale options (key, scale type, In
      Key/Chromatic, and Fixed Y/N) are saved with the Set.
    </p>

    <h3 id="step-sequencing-melodies-and-harmonies">
      Step Sequencing Melodies and Harmonies
    </h3>
    <p>
      In addition to playing and recording in real time, you can also step
      sequence your melodies and harmonies. To toggle to the Melodic Sequencer,
      press the <kbd>Note Mode</kbd> button a second time.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushMSSLayout.png"
        alt="The Pad Grid When Step Sequencing Pitches"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>The Pad Grid When Step Sequencing Pitches</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      With In Key selected, each row corresponds to one of the available pitches
      in the currently selected scale. With Chromatic selected, notes that are
      in the key are lit, while notes that are not in the key are unlit. The
      light blue row (which is the bottom row by default) indicates the root of
      the selected key. Each column of pads represents a step in the resolution
      set by the <kbd>Scene/Grid</kbd> buttons.
    </p>
    <p>
      As with the real-time playing layout, pressing the <kbd>Octave Up</kbd> and
      <kbd>Down</kbd> button shifts the range of available notes. You can also use
      the touch strip to change the range. Hold the <kbd>Shift</kbd> key while adjusting
      the touch strip or pressing the Octave buttons to fine tune the pitch range.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushDisplayNoteRange.png"
        alt="The Display Shows the Range of Available Notes"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>The Display Shows the Range of Available Notes</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Pressing <kbd>Note</kbd> again will toggle to the Melodic Sequencer + 32 Notes
      layout.
    </p>
    <p>
      In addition to adding and removing notes, you can also adjust the velocity
      and micro-timing of the notes.
    </p>

    <h4 id="adjusting-the-loop-length">Adjusting the Loop Length</h4>
    <p>
      The loop length controls allow you to set the length of the clip's loop
      and determine which part of it you can see and edit in the melodic and
      drum step sequencers. Each loop length pad corresponds to a page of steps.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushLoopControls.png"
        alt="Each Loop Length Pad Corresponds to One Page"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Each Loop Length Pad Corresponds to One Page</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      To change the loop length, hold one pad and then tap another pad or, to
      set the loop length to exactly one page, quickly double-tap the
      corresponding pad.
    </p>
    <p>
      Note that the page you see is not necessarily the page you hear. To edit a
      single page of a longer loop while still allowing the loop to play for the
      full length, single-tap the pad that corresponds to that page. This will
      "lock" the view to that page without changing the loop length.
    </p>
    <p>The pad colors in the loop length section indicate the following:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Unlit</strong> — this page is outside of the loop.</li>
      <li>
        <strong>White</strong> — this page is within the loop, but is not currently
        visible in the step sequencer section.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Dull yellow</strong> — this page is visible in the step sequencer
        section, but is not currently playing.
      </li>
      <li><strong>Green</strong> — this is the currently playing page.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      To duplicate the contents of a sequencer page, hold <kbd>Duplicate</kbd>,
      press the loop length pad for the page you want to duplicate, and press
      the loop length pad for the destination page. To remove notes first, hold <kbd
        >Delete</kbd
      > and tap the loop length pad for that page.
    </p>

    <h3 id="melodic-sequencer-32-notes">Melodic Sequencer + 32 Notes</h3>
    <p>
      The Melodic Sequencer + 32 Notes layout combines both step sequencing and
      real-time playing capabilities. Providing access to multiple octaves and
      steps on a single page, this layout is ideal for figuring out chords and
      harmonies to sequence and well suited to longer phrases.
    </p>

    <h4 id="32-notes">32 Notes</h4>
    <p>
      The bottom half of the pad grid lets you play notes in real-time, and
      select them for step sequencing. Each pad corresponds to one of the
      available pitches in the currently selected scale. Pressing a pad will
      select and play the note. Selected notes are represented by a lighter
      version of the track's color.
    </p>
    <p>
      To select a pad without triggering it, press and hold the <kbd>Select</kbd
      > button while tapping a pad.
    </p>
    <p>The pad colors indicate the following:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Blue</strong> — this note is the root note of the scale.</li>
      <li><strong>Blue-Green</strong> — this pad is selected.</li>
      <li><strong>Green</strong> — this pad is currently playing.</li>
      <li>
        <strong>White</strong> — this note is in the scale, but is not the root.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Pressing the <kbd>Octave Up</kbd> or <kbd>Down</kbd> button shifts the range
      of available notes. Hold the <kbd>Shift</kbd> key while pressing the Octave
      buttons to shift by one note in the scale.
    </p>

    <h4 id="sequencer">Sequencer</h4>
    <p>
      Tapping a step in the top half of the pad grid adds all selected notes to
      that step. Steps containing notes are displayed in a blue color.
    </p>
    <p>
      Holding a step lets you view notes contained within the step. Tapping any
      of these selected notes will remove it from the step. Holding multiple
      steps will add selected notes to all those steps.
    </p>
    <p>
      While holding <kbd>Duplicate</kbd>, you can press a step to copy the notes
      in that step and then press another step to paste them to a new location.
    </p>
    <p>The pad colors in the step sequencer indicate the following:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Blue</strong> — this step contains a note.</li>
      <li><strong>Green</strong> — this step is currently playing.</li>
      <li><strong>White</strong> — this step is selected.</li>
      <li>
        <strong>Dull Yellow</strong> — this step contains a note, but the note is
        muted.
      </li>
      <li><strong>Gray</strong> — this pad is empty.</li>
      <li>
        <strong>Light Red</strong> — these pads are not active when triplets are selected
        as the step size.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h3 id="navigating-in-note-mode">Navigating in Note Mode</h3>
    <p>The Arrow Keys allow you to move between tracks.</p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushArrowKeys.png"
        alt="Arrow Keys"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Arrow Keys</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      The Left/Right Arrows move between tracks. Note that selecting a MIDI
      track on Push 1 automatically arms it, so it can be played immediately. In
      Live, track Arm buttons will appear pink to indicate that they have been
      armed via selection.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/ArmButtonPink.png"
        alt="Pink Track Arm Button"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Pink Track Arm Button</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      The specific behavior of the Up/Down Arrows is determined by the Workflow
      mode set in Push 1's User Preferences. In both modes, the Up/Down Arrows
      move up or down by a single scene. In Scene Workflow, the selected scene
      is triggered. In Clip Workflow, only the selected track's clip is
      triggered.
    </p>
    <p>
      Navigating with the Up/Down Arrows in Note Mode always begins playback
      immediately, and a triggered clip will take over the play position from
      whatever clip was played in that track before.
    </p>

    <h3 id="controlling-instruments-and-effects">
      Controlling Live's Instruments and Effects
    </h3>
    <p>
      Pressing the <kbd>Device</kbd> button puts Push 1 in Device Mode, which allows
      Push 1's encoders to control parameters in Live's devices.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushDeviceButton.png"
        alt="Device Button"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Device Button</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      In Device Mode, the Selection Control buttons select devices in the
      currently selected track, while the State Control buttons turn the
      selected device on or off. The currently selected device is marked with an
      arrow in the display.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushDeviceMode.png"
        alt="Device Mode Settings"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Device Mode Settings</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      The <kbd>In</kbd> and <kbd>Out</kbd> buttons allow you to navigate to additional
      devices and parameters, including additional banks of parameters and additional
      device chains within Racks that contain more than one chain.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushInOutButtons.png"
        alt="In and Out Buttons"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>In and Out Buttons</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h3 id="mixing-with-push-1">Mixing with Push 1</h3>
    <p>
      To control volumes, pans, or sends with the encoders for up to eight
      tracks simultaneously, press the corresponding button on Push 1. Hold <kbd
        >Shift</kbd
      > while adjusting the encoders for fine-tune control.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushVolumePanSendButtons.png"
        alt="Volume and Pan & Send Buttons"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Volume and Pan &amp; Send Buttons</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <ul>
      <li>
        In <strong>Volume Mode</strong>, the encoders control track volume.
      </li>
      <li>
        Pressing the <strong><kbd>Pan &amp; Send</kbd></strong> button repeatedly
        will cycle between controlling pans and however many sends are available in
        your Live Set.
      </li>
      <li>
        In <strong>Track Mode</strong>, the encoders control track volume, pan
        and the first six sends of the selected track.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushTrackButton.png"
        alt="Track Button"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Track Button</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushTrackModeSelection.png"
        alt="Selecting Tracks in Track Mode"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Selecting Tracks in Track Mode</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Press the <kbd>Master</kbd> button to select the Main track. Press and hold
      a Group Track's Selection Control button to unfold or fold the track.
    </p>

    <h3 id="recording-automation">Recording Automation</h3>
    <p>
      Changes that you make to device and mixer parameters can be recorded to
      your clips as automation, so that the sound will change over time as the
      clip plays. To record automation, press Push 1's <kbd>Automation</kbd> button.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushAutomationButton.png"
        alt="Automation Button"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Automation Button</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      This toggles Live's Session Automation Arm button, allowing you to record
      changes you make to Push 1's encoders as part of the clip. When you're
      done recording parameter changes, press the <kbd>Automation</kbd> button again
      to turn it off.
    </p>
    <p>
      To delete the changes you've recorded for a particular parameter, press
      and hold the <kbd>Delete</kbd> button and touch the corresponding encoder. If
      automation hasn't been recorded for a parameter, holding <kbd>Delete</kbd> and
      touching an encoder will reset the corresponding parameter to its default value.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushDisplayAutomatedParameter.png"
        alt="Automated and/or Overridden Parameters are Indicated in the Display"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>
        Automated and/or Overridden Parameters are Indicated in the Display
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      To reenable all automation that you have manually overridden, press and
      hold <kbd>Shift</kbd> and press the <kbd>Automation</kbd> button.
    </p>

    <h3 id="step-sequencing-automation">Step Sequencing Automation</h3>
    <p>
      In both the drum and melodic step sequencers, it's possible to automate
      parameters for the selected step.
    </p>

    <h4 id="note-specific-parameters">Note-Specific Parameters</h4>
    <p>
      When working in any sequencing layout in Clip Mode, you can adjust note
      settings for each step. To access these settings, simply press and hold a
      step.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushHeldStepDisplay.png"
        alt="Hold a Step to Adjust Note and Automation Parameters"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>
        Hold a Step to Adjust Note and Automation Parameters
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>You can then adjust the corresponding encoders in order to:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Nudge notes backwards or forwards in time.</li>
      <li>Adjust the coarse Length of the selected notes.</li>
      <li>Fine-tune the length adjustment of the selected notes.</li>
      <li>Change the Velocity of the selected notes.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      You can also adjust these note-specific parameters for multiple steps at
      the same time. To do this, press and hold all of the pads you'd like to
      adjust, and then tweak the encoders.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushMultipleNoteParameters.png"
        alt="With Multiple Steps Selected, the Display Shows the Range of Parameter Values"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>
        With Multiple Steps Selected, the Display Shows the Range of Parameter
        Values
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      You can also create notes with your desired Nudge, Length, and Velocity
      values by holding an empty step and then tweaking any of these encoders.
    </p>
    <p>
      When working with drums, you can adjust nudge, length, and velocity for
      every note played by a particular pad by pressing and holding the <kbd
        >Select</kbd
      > button, pressing the pad, and then adjusting the encoders.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushDrumPadEditing.png"
        alt="Hold Select and Press a Drum Pad to Tweak All Notes Played by that Pad"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>
        Hold <kbd>Select</kbd> and Press a Drum Pad to Tweak All Notes Played by that
        Pad
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      In both the drum and melodic step sequencers, you can copy a step
      (including all of its note-specific parameters) and paste it to another
      step. To do this, hold <kbd>Duplicate</kbd> and tap the step you'd like to copy,
      then tap the destination step and release <kbd>Duplicate</kbd>.
    </p>

    <h4 id="per-step-automation">Per-Step Automation</h4>
    <p>
      When in Device Mode or Volume Mode, hold one or more steps in order to
      create and edit device or mixer automation for only the selected step(s).
      While holding a step and tweaking an encoder, the corresponding
      parameter's automation value will be adjusted specifically for the time
      represented by that step. Note that per-step automation can be created for
      any step, even if that step doesn't contain notes.
    </p>

    <h3 id="controlling-session-view">Controlling Live's Session View</h3>
    <p>
      Press Push 1's <kbd>Session</kbd> button to switch from Note Mode to Session
      Mode. You can press and hold the <kbd>Session</kbd> button to temporarily toggle
      Session Mode.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushSessionButton.png"
        alt="Session Button"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Session Button</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      In Session Mode, the 8x8 pad grid will launch clips and the Scene/Grid
      Buttons will launch scenes. Pressing a pad triggers the clip in the
      corresponding location in Live's Session View. If the track is selected,
      pressing the button records a new clip.
    </p>
    <p>The pads light up in different colors so you know what's going on:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        The color of all non-playing clips in your Live Set is reflected on the
        pads.
      </li>
      <li>Playing clips pulse green to white.</li>
      <li>Recording clips pulse red to white.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      You can stop all music in a track by enabling Stop Mode and pressing that
      track's State Control button.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushStopClips.png"
        alt="Stopping Clip Playback"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>Stopping Clip Playback</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      To stop all clips, press and hold <kbd>Shift</kbd>, and then press <kbd
        >Stop</kbd
      >.
    </p>
    <p>
      The directional arrows and <kbd>Shift</kbd> button increase the scope of the
      eight-by-eight grid. Pressing <kbd>Up</kbd> or <kbd>Down</kbd> moves you up
      or down one scene at a time. Hold the <kbd>Shift</kbd> button while hitting
      <kbd>Up</kbd> or <kbd>Down</kbd> to move eight scenes up or down. The <kbd
        >Left</kbd
      > and <kbd>Right</kbd> arrow keys move you left or right one track at a time.
      Hold <kbd>Shift</kbd> while hitting <kbd>Left</kbd> or <kbd>Right</kbd> to move
      eight tracks at a time.
    </p>

    <h4 id="session-overview">Session Overview</h4>
    <p>
      Push 1's Session Overview lets you navigate through large Live Sets
      quickly without looking at your computer screen. Hold down the <kbd
        >Shift</kbd
      > button and the pad grid zooms out to reveal an overview of your Session View.
      In the Session Overview, each pad represents an eight-scene-by-eight-track block
      of clips, giving you a matrix of 64 scenes by 64 tracks.
    </p>
    <p>Color coding in the Session Overview:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Amber:</strong> indicates the currently selected block of clips.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Green:</strong> there are clips playing in that block of clips.
      </li>
      <li><strong>Red:</strong> there are no clips playing in that range.</li>
      <li>
        <strong>No color:</strong> there are no tracks or scenes in that range.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h3 id="setting-user-preferences">Setting User Preferences</h3>
    <p>
      Press and hold the <kbd>User</kbd> button to adjust the sensitivity of Push
      1's velocity response, aftertouch, and other settings.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushUserButton.png"
        alt="User Button"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>User Button</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <figure>
      <img
        src="https://ableton-production.imgix.net/live-manual/12/PushUserSettings.png"
        alt="User Settings"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>User Settings</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Pad Threshold</strong> sets the softest playing force that will trigger
        notes. More force is required at higher settings.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Velocity Curve</strong> determines how sensitive the pads are when
        hit with various amounts of force, ranging from Linear to various logarithmic
        curves. Higher Log values provide more dynamic range when playing softly.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Workflow</strong> determines how Push 1 behaves when the <kbd
          >Duplicate</kbd
        >, <kbd>New</kbd>, or Up/Down arrow buttons are pressed.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Aftertouch Threshold</strong> sets the lowest incoming aftertouch
        value (from 0–127) that Push will register. Input values below this level
        will be ignored, while input values above this level will be scaled across
        the entire aftertouch range.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      <strong>Scene Workflow</strong> (default): <kbd>Duplicate</kbd> creates a new
      scene containing all of the currently playing clips. <kbd>New</kbd> is identical
      to <kbd>Duplicate</kbd>, except that it does not duplicate the currently
      selected clip. The Up/Down Arrows move up or down by a single scene with
      seamless playback.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Clip Workflow:</strong>
      <kbd>Duplicate</kbd> creates a copy of the currently selected clip in the next
      clip slot. <kbd>New</kbd> prepares an empty clip slot on the currently selected
      track. The Up/Down Arrows move up or down by a single scene; only the selected
      track's clip is triggered.
    </p>

    <h3 id="push-1-control-reference">Push 1 Control Reference</h3>

    <h4>Focus/Navigation Section</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong><kbd>Note Mode</kbd></strong> — When selected, the Pad Section changes
        its functionality based on the type of track selected: instrument tracks play
        notes and toggle between real-time playing and melodic step sequencing; Drum
        Rack tracks divide the pad section for playing, loop length, and step sequencing.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><kbd>Session Mode</kbd></strong> — When selected, the Pad Section
        launches clips in Live's Session View.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><kbd>Shift</kbd></strong> — Press and hold while pressing other buttons
        to access additional functionality.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Arrow Keys</strong> — Move through your Live Set (in Session Mode)
        and between tracks or scenes/clips (in Note Mode).
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><kbd>Select</kbd></strong> — In Session Mode, hold and press a clip
        to select it without launching. In Note Mode, hold and press a Drum Rack pad
        to select its notes without triggering the pad.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Add Section</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong><kbd>Add Effect</kbd></strong> — Opens Browse Mode to add a new device
        to the right of the currently selected device. Hold <kbd>Shift</kbd> while
        pressing <kbd>Add Effect</kbd> to add to the left. To add a MIDI Effect, first
        select the instrument, then hold <kbd>Shift</kbd> while pressing <kbd
          >Add Effect</kbd
        >.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><kbd>Add Track</kbd></strong> — Creates a new MIDI track to the right
        of the currently selected track. Press and hold to select a different type
        of track (Audio, MIDI, or Return).
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Note Section</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong><kbd>Scales</kbd></strong> — When Note Mode is on and an instrument
        track is selected, allows you to select which scale will be played on the
        pads.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><kbd>User</kbd></strong> — All of Push 1's built-in functionality
        can be disabled via User Mode, allowing Push 1 to be reprogrammed for alternate
        functions.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><kbd>Repeat</kbd></strong> — When enabled, holding down a pad will
        retrigger the note. The <kbd>Scene/Grid</kbd> buttons change the rhythmic
        value of the repeated note.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><kbd>Accent</kbd></strong> — When enabled, all incoming notes are
        played at full velocity. Press and hold <kbd>Accent</kbd> to temporarily enable
        it.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><kbd>Octave Up</kbd>/<kbd>Down</kbd></strong> — Shift the pads up
        or down by octave (instruments), up/down by 16 pads (Drum Racks), or up/down
        by eight scenes (Session Mode).
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Transport Section</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong><kbd>Fixed Length</kbd></strong> — When enabled, all newly created
        clips will be a fixed number of bars. Press and hold, then use the buttons
        beneath the display to specify the length.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><kbd>Automation</kbd></strong> — Toggles Live's Automation Record
        button. Hold <kbd>Shift</kbd> and press to reenable overridden automation.
        Hold <kbd>Delete</kbd> and press to delete all automation in a clip.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><kbd>Duplicate</kbd></strong> — In Scene Workflow, creates a new scene
        containing all currently playing clips. In Clip Workflow, creates a copy of
        the currently selected clip.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><kbd>New</kbd></strong> — Stops the selected clip and prepares Live
        to record new material. On armed MIDI tracks, holding <kbd>Record</kbd> while
        pressing <kbd>New</kbd> triggers Capture MIDI.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><kbd>Record</kbd></strong> — Begin recording. Pressing again stops
        recording but continues playback. A third press enables overdub mode.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><kbd>Play/Stop</kbd></strong> — Toggles the play button in Live's
        Control Bar. Hold <kbd>Shift</kbd> while pressing to return Live's transport
        to 1.1.1 without starting playback.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Tempo Section</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong><kbd>Tap Tempo</kbd></strong> — Press once every beat to set the tempo
        of the Live Set to your tapping.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><kbd>Metronome</kbd></strong> — Toggles Live's metronome on or off.
      </li>
      <li>
        The left encoder adjusts Live's tempo in increments of one BPM. Holding <kbd
          >Shift</kbd
        > adjusts in increments of .1 BPM.
      </li>
      <li>
        The right encoder sets the amount of swing applied when Quantizing.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Edit Section</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong><kbd>Undo</kbd></strong> — Undoes the last action. Press and hold
        <kbd>Shift</kbd> while pressing <kbd>Undo</kbd> to Redo.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><kbd>Delete</kbd></strong> — In Note Mode, deletes the selected clip.
        Hold <kbd>Delete</kbd> and press a clip, device, or track to delete. Hold
        <kbd>Delete</kbd> and touch an encoder to delete automation.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><kbd>Quantize</kbd></strong> — Press and release to quantize selected
        notes. Hold and press a drum pad to quantize that pad's notes. Press and hold
        to access quantization settings.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><kbd>Double</kbd></strong> — Doubles the material within the loop,
        as well as the length of the loop.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Touch Strip</h4>
    <p>
      When an instrument track is selected, the touch strip adjusts pitch bend
      or modulation wheel amount when playing in real-time, or the available
      range of notes when step sequencing. When a Drum Rack track is selected,
      the touch strip selects the Drum Rack bank.
    </p>
    <p>
      Pitch bend is selected by default. To change the functionality of the
      touch strip, hold <kbd>Select</kbd> and tap the strip. This toggles between
      pitch bend and mod wheel functionality.
    </p>

    <h4>Using Footswitches with Push 1</h4>
    <p>
      Two ports on the back of Push 1 allow you to connect momentary
      footswitches. Footswitch 1 acts as a sustain pedal. Footswitch 2 gives you
      hands-free control of Push 1's recording functionality — a single tap
      toggles the <kbd>Record</kbd> button, while quickly double-tapping is the same
      as pressing the <kbd>New</kbd> button.
    </p>
    <p>
      Note that certain footswitches may behave "backwards." Footswitch polarity
      can usually be corrected by connecting the footswitch to the port while
      depressing it, but we recommend using footswitches with a physical
      polarity switch.
    </p>

    <p class="manual-source">
      Content sourced from the <a
        href="https://www.ableton.com/en/manual/using-push-1/"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
        >Ableton Live 12 Reference Manual, Chapter 34</a
      >.
    </p>
  </div>
</MainLayout>

